"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901221","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>Although not covered by the draft Withdrawal Agreement, it is our intention that family members of UK nationals who have exercised their free movement rights in another EU Member State before returning to the UK prior to the end of the implementation period, as per Surinder Singh case law, will be eligible for the UK’s settled status scheme.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-14T17:00:38.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901221/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901221/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether non-EU citizens who are spouses of British nationals and exercise free movement rights under the Surinder Singh principle are included in the citizens' rights agreement reached with the EU and will be eligible to apply for the settled status scheme.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","142885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901222","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>The compensation paid to elected, co-opted and appointed members of the eight English Headteacher Boards (HTBs) was £472,530 for 2017/18. For 2018/19 that cost is expected to be approximately £450,000. The Department has not yet profiled the budget for years beyond 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>The schools/trusts of each HTB member are paid £500 per day when head teachers attend HTB meetings, plus in some cases, £250 for half-day reading/prep time. If HTB members are not serving head teachers, this money is paid directly to them.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-15T15:46:25.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901222/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901222/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Headteachers: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to his Department was of headteacher boards in 2017-18; and what estimate he has made of the potential cost of those boards in each year up to 2023.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","142872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901223","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>Related party transactions involving academy trusts encompass both receipts by and payments by trusts and so there are separate totals for each. The information requested, including both payments made by and receipts received by academy trusts, was included for the first time in the Academies Sector Annual Report and Accounts for the academic year 2015 to 2016.</p><p>Payments made by academy trusts to related parties:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Related Party Transactions</p></td><td><p>2015/16 payments to related parties (£000)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£1 to £50,000</p></td><td><p>2,636</p></td><td><p>24,627</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£50,001 to £100,000</p></td><td><p>183</p></td><td><p>12,585</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£100,001 to £200,000</p></td><td><p>119</p></td><td><p>16,006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£200,001 to £250,000</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>5,662</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£250,001+</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>61,922</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>3,033</p></td><td><p>120,802</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Income received by academy trusts from related parties:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Related Party Transactions</p></td><td><p>2015/16 receipts from related parties (£000)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£1 to £50,000</p></td><td><p>857</p></td><td><p>9,574</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£50,001 to £100,000</p></td><td><p>135</p></td><td><p>9,541</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£100,001 to £200,000</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>11,471</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£200,001 to £250,000</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>3,565</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£250,001+</p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>39,066</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>1,155</p></td><td><p>73,217</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As the tables above show, £120,802,000 (62%) of the total value of all related party transactions is accounted for by academy trusts making payments to related parties, whilst £73,217,000 (38%) represents income received by academy trusts from related parties. Income received from related parties includes: transactions with subsidiary companies or shared services, diocesan education authorities, related charities as well as donations or services provided by trustees, or trustees’ family members.</p><p> </p><p>This information was not previously collected in this format and we do not have comparable analysis for previous years.</p><p> </p><p>Academy trusts are required to disclose all related party transactions in their audited annual accounts, which are publicly available for all years the academy trust has been in operation.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-23T16:10:14.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901223/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901223/answer","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901223/answer/previousversion/58121","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the total value was of related party transactions made by academies and academy trusts in (a) the year ending 31 August 2016 and (b)  each of the previous five years.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","142873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901224","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>The department has no plans to change the requirement for the £200 contribution to the cost of computer equipment and has made no assessment of the potential cost of doing so. Computers are a mainstream cost for all students and it is right therefore that students eligible for the Disabled Students Allowance (DSA) should contribute towards the cost of their DSAs-recommended computer equipment.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-15T15:35:33.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901224/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901224/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2018 to Question 139972 on Disabled Students' Allowances,  what estimate he has made of the potential cost to the public purse of funding the £200 contribution made by students in receipt of Disabled Students’ Allowance for the purchase of computer hardware in each year up to 2023.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","142874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901225","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-17","<p>Under the Theft Act 1968, the maximum penalty for the theft of a pet is 7 years’ imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>The Sentencing Council updated its guidelines in relation to sentencing for theft offences in February 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The guidelines take account of the emotional distress and therefore harm that theft of personal items such as a pet can have on the victim and accordingly recommends higher penalties for such offences.</p><p> </p><p>Since 6 April 2016, all dogs in England and Wales must be microchipped and registered to an approved database by the time they are eight weeks old. In addition to reuniting lost or stolen dogs with their owners, this will also help to reduce the numbers of strays that have to be kennelled and re-homed by local authorities and dog re-homing charities.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-17T15:45:15.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901225/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901225/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Pets: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of the Theft Act 1968 on deterring the theft of pets.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","142757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901226","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-18","<p>The Government shares the British public’s high regard for animal welfare and, after we leave the EU, the Government plans to retain the current regulations relating to fur imports. Strict rules apply to fur farming in the EU and there are legal frameworks for the farming of fur animals in some non-EU countries, including minimum standards and welfare inspections. Many major fur companies also have their own standards that they audit with their producers.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-18T08:37:55.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901226/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901226/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Furs: Farms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of animal welfare in fur farms in (a) Poland, (b) Finland, (c) China and (d) France that export fur to the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","142758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901227","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Government monitors events in Bahrain closely. We regularly raise human rights concerns with the Bahraini authorities in private and in public and will continue to do so. We encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments.</p><p>We encourage those with concerns about the treatment of prisoners in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We encourage these oversight bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-15T16:20:39.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901227/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901227/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Bahrain: Torture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of reports of alleged use of torture and forced confessions in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","142764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901228","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>We are working in close partnership with the Federal Republic of Nigeria and Socialist Republic of Vietnam to combat modern slavery and human trafficking. We have a strong information-sharing relationship and are working to build the capacity of both countries to support victims and bring perpetrators to justice through the Modern Slavery Fund and Conflict, Stability and Security Fund.</p><p>There is currently no Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on human trafficking between the Home Office and the Socialist Republic of Vietnam. However, the UK is working to develop an MoU on human trafficking to enable greater cooperation to apprehend perpetrators and support those at risk.</p><p>There is a 2004 Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the Federal Republic of Nigeria on Cooperation to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons. The MoU is primarily a ‘statement of goodwill’ and has helped to facilitate international cooperation between the UK and Nigeria to combat human trafficking.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","142864","2018-06-05T15:07:56.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901228/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901228/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Human Trafficking: Vietnam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the effect of his Department’s memorandum of understanding with the Socialist Republic of Vietnam on the improvement of (a) identification, (b) notification, (c) referral and (d) assisted voluntary return of victims and potential victims of human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","142863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901229","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Open University (OU) plays an important role in the higher education sector. Department for Education officials have met with senior staff from the OU and I am due to meet with both its interim and immediate former vice chancellors.</p><p>The government and the Office for Students (OfS) monitor the financial sustainability of the higher education sector in England. The OfS monitors the financial sustainability of individual providers in receipt of public funding, including the OU.</p><p>The independent panel supporting the review of post-18 education and funding recently concluded a call for evidence process which invited all interested parties to submit evidence to inform its work.</p><p>The government has provided £48 million to support teaching in 2017 to 2018 at the OU, including funds to support part-time students.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-15T16:20:26.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901229/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901229/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Open University: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations he has received on the effect of changes to higher education funding on the Open University.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","142765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901230","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>We are working in close partnership with the Federal Republic of Nigeria and Socialist Republic of Vietnam to combat modern slavery and human trafficking. We have a strong information-sharing relationship and are working to build the capacity of both countries to support victims and bring perpetrators to justice through the Modern Slavery Fund and Conflict, Stability and Security Fund.</p><p>There is currently no Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on human trafficking between the Home Office and the Socialist Republic of Vietnam. However, the UK is working to develop an MoU on human trafficking to enable greater cooperation to apprehend perpetrators and support those at risk.</p><p>There is a 2004 Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the Federal Republic of Nigeria on Cooperation to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons. The MoU is primarily a ‘statement of goodwill’ and has helped to facilitate international cooperation between the UK and Nigeria to combat human trafficking.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","142863","2018-06-05T15:07:56.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901230/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901230/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Human Trafficking: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the effect of his Department’s memorandum of understanding with the Federal Republic of Nigeria on the improvement of (a) identification, (b) notification, (c) referral and (d) assisted voluntary return of victims and potential victims of human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","142864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901231","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>Records of disqualification orders are not held centrally.</p><p>Records of the number of offenders convicted of animal welfare offences are held by the Ministry of Justice. However, records of disqualification orders made under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 are not routinely held by that department, but are held on the Police National Computer. To breach a disqualification order is an offence and therefore numbers of breaches are held by the Ministry of Justice.</p><p>Although records of disqualification orders are held on the Police National Computer, because of the way they are recorded it is not possible to link the number made under the 2006 Act to the number of convictions under the same Act.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T15:47:34.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901231/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901231/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Animal Welfare: Disqualification Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many disqualification orders have been issued in England and Wales under s34 of the Animal Welfare Act 2006 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","142790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901232","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>I refer the Rt. Hon. Member to the reply given to the Hon. Member for Nottingham North, on 2 May 2018, PQ UIN 137656.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:23:08.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901232/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901232/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Animal Welfare: Disqualification Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many disqualification orders under s34 of the Animal Welfare Act 2006 have been breached in England and Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","142791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901233","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Government has set out several public commitments, including in the Budget and in the Confidence and Supply Agreement, to work towards a ‘comprehensive and ambitious’ set of City Deals across Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>Negotiations have been opened for a Belfast City Regions deal; however, a timetable has not been set to deliver a City Deal for Belfast or for Londonderry. A timetable cannot be agreed until proposals are completed and submitted to Government. Officials from across Whitehall and the Northern Ireland Civil Service have been engaging with partners on their proposals.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-05-15T10:46:21.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901233/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901233/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-10","City Deals: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the timescale is for the Belfast and Londonderry city deals to become fully operational.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","142780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901234","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>Page 7 refers to the requirement to know the results from the continuous emissions monitoring systems (which measure total particulate matter). The results are needed to select an appropriate sampling duration to carry out the discontinuous monitoring of PM10 and PM2.5.</p><p> </p><p>Page 9 refers to techniques for the continuous measurement of PM10 and PM2.5 in ambient air and not in the exhaust gases from the stacks (chimneys) of processes such as waste incinerators (for which there is no commercially available equipment).</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:17:40.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901234/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901234/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2018 to Question 135379, and the reference therein to there being no commercially available equipment for monitoring emissions of PM10 and PM2.5, to what sort of equipment the references on pages 7 and 9 of the Technical Guidance Note M15 on Monitoring PM10 and PM2.5 refer which give advice about continuous monitoring of PM10, PM2.5 and PM1.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","142749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901235","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>The answer to Question 135379 referred to the fact that there is no commercially available equipment for the continuous monitoring of PM10 and PM2.5. The Environment Agency is aware that there have been a limited number of research projects undertaken by academic or research institutes around the world which have attempted to adapt ambient monitoring techniques for PM10 and PM2.5 to stack (chimney) emissions monitoring, but these would have been installed for short periods of time and so do not provide continuous monitoring results. The Environment Agency is not aware of any other examples of non-commercially available equipment for measuring emissions of PM10 and PM2.5.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:26:48.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901235/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901235/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer to of 19 April 2018 to Question 135379, what non-commercially available equipment there is for measuring emissions of PM10 and PM2.5.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","142750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901236","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>The Environment Agency requires operators to continuously monitor atmospheric emissions of total particulate matter, which are comprised of PM2.5, PM10 and other particulates.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:10:21.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901236/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901236/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2017 to Question 117197 on Incinerators, who undertakes the strict monitoring regime for emissions of PM 10 and PM 2.5.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","142751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901237","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-16","<p>​A Carte de Séjour is a residency document. <em>We advise all British people overseas to ensure their documentation is up to date. British residents of France do not require a Carte de Sejour, but are entitled to one. We will continue to discuss with the French authorities the future registration requirements for those UK nationals in France covered by the UK-EU Withdrawal Agreement, and we will update the British community in due course.</em></p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-16T17:24:11.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901237/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901237/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","France: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether it is his Department's policy to advise British citizens living in France to obtain a Carte de Sejour.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","142742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901238","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>In order to decide whether to grant an environmental permit to operate a new incinerator, the Environment Agency is required to consider all emissions arising from activities carried out within the permit boundary of the proposed site, including emissions arising from vehicle movements. Assessment of the impact of emissions from vehicle movements to and from the site is the responsibility of the local planning authority.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:15:03.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901238/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901238/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of (a) the additional amount of extra traffic caused by a waste incinerator being in use and (b) the increase in emissions of (i) PM10, (ii) PM2.5, (iii) PM 1 and (iv) PM0.1 caused by that extra traffic.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","142752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901239","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-15","<p>The UK Government is strongly committed to meeting the needs of internally displaced persons (IDPs). We published a new Humanitarian Reform Policy in October last year which includes a focus on forced displacement and measures that are relevant for mitigating and responding more effectively to displacement. We believe our primary focus should now be at the global level to press for a more effective international response. For example, several UN Member States, including the UK, are now actively exploring options with the UN – including the idea of launching a UN High Level Panel on Internally Displaced Persons, which presents one way of galvanising greater political and operational attention and action on IDPs.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-15T14:35:36.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901239/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901239/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Internally Displaced People: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will develop a cross-departmental strategy for the UK’s approach to supporting the (a) prevention of, (b) protection of and (c) solution to the increasing number of internally displaced people around the world.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","142755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901240","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>We welcome the findings in the Children’s Society ‘Crumbling Futures’ report and agree that this is a difficult and important transition. The government is committed to ensuring that vulnerable children are ready for adult life and is taking action to ensure that services protect and support children. We recognise the importance of avoiding ‘cliff edges’ in support for the most vulnerable children and the offer of support from local authorities now extends to all care leavers up to 25. ‘Working Together to Safeguard Children’ makes it clear that when children on Child Protection Plans reach 18, local authorities should consider whether support services are still required.</p><p> </p><p>As a priority, we are taking forward a review of the educational outcomes of Children in Need. This review and call for evidence, which was launched on 16 March 2018, is looking at the quality of support provided to all Children in Need including 16 and 17 year olds. We will consider the full range of views we receive in response to the call for evidence, including any around transition to adult services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are delivering a major programme of reform to improve the support provided to Children in Need. As set out in ‘Putting Children First’ (2016), we are working to improve the quality of the workforce, develop and spread innovative practice, and improve the quality of local authority children’s services. We are also using the Department for Education’s Social Care Innovation Programme to trial programmes to improve the quality of support for adolescents, including assessing how early help and contextual safeguarding can help protect them from the specific threats they face.</p><p> </p><p>A key finding of ‘Crumbling Futures’ is that the mental health needs of children and young people appear to be one of the main issues affecting older adolescents as they progress into adulthood. The new Mental Health Support Teams proposed in the government’s Mental Health green paper will provide significant support to 16 to 18 year olds in schools and colleges. The Department for Education will also test how the teams can support vulnerable 16 to 18 year olds and other young people not in school or college, such as those in apprenticeships and other work-based learning. Additionally, the Department of Health and Social Care is setting up a new national strategic partnership with key stakeholders focused on improving the mental health of 16 to 25 year olds by encouraging more coordinated action, experimentation and robust evaluation.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-15T15:39:49.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901240/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901240/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the report Crumbling Futures published by the Children's Society in March 2018, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that 16 and 17-year-olds referred to children’s services are receiving adequate support as they transition into adulthood.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","142756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901241","Cabinet Office","true","2018-05-15","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-05-15T13:53:44.293Z","2018-05-16T12:24:02.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901241/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901241/answer","PQ142781.pdf","PQ142781.pdf","UKSA Response ","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901241/answer","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901241/answer/previousversion/57966","Biography information for Chloe Smith","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-10","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the five most common cancer diagnoses were among (a) men and (b) women in (i) 2007 and (ii) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","142781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901242","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-17","<p>The number of custodial sentences issued to female offenders in England and Wales, by court type and police force area from 2012 to 2016, can be viewed in the attached Tables 1 to 5. The data for 2017 will be published on 17 May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to doing all we can to address the issues around female offending so we can better protect the public and deliver more effective rehabilitation. That is why we will set out a strategy for female offenders, to improve outcomes and services for women in both the community and custody.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-05-17T16:23:18.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901242/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901242/answer","PQ 142767 table.xlsx","PQ 142767 table.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901242/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-10","Prison Sentences: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women were sent to immediate custody from the (a) the Crown Court and (b) magistrates' courts for sentences (i) below 6 months and (ii) above 6 months in each police force area in England and Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","142767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901243","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 14 November 2017 to PQ UIN 112856.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:07:07.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901243/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901243/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Squirrels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the change in the (a) grey and (b) red squirrel populations between 2007 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","142782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901244","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-15","<p>We do not hold this information. The BBC is responsible for the administration, collection and enforcement of the licence fee regime.​</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-05-15T09:52:59.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901244/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901244/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-10","Television: Licencsng","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the loss of revenue to the public purse as a result of television licence fee evasion in (a) 2012 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","142783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901245","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-18","<p>The Government’s £1.2 billion Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy outlines the significant investment that is being made to support cycling of all kinds, including cycling on electrically assisted pedal cycles (or “e-bikes”). The Government agrees that e-bikes have significant potential to increase the overall amount of cycling, and the Strategy will help increase the use of both conventional bikes and e-bikes.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-18T09:40:55.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901245/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901245/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Electric Vehicles: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding he plans to make available from the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy to increase the use of electric bikes.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","142877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901246","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-18","<p>The Cycle to Work scheme can already be used to assist with the purchase of electrically assisted pedal cycles, and is one of the many ways in which the Government is supporting active travel choices, as set out in the 2017 Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy. The Department has not made any formal assessment of the number of electrically assisted pedal cycles which have been purchased under the scheme.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-18T09:47:59.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901246/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901246/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Electric Vehicles: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of using the Cycle to Work Scheme to support the uptake of electric bikes.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","142878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901247","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-18","<p>The Government’s Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, published in April 2017, summarised the Government’s overall strategy to make cycling and walking the natural choice for shorter journeys. The measures set out in the Strategy, such as the investment that is being made in improved cycle infrastructure, will help to increase all forms of cycling, including cycling on an electrically assisted pedal cycle (or “e-bike”). The Government’s Cycle to Work scheme can also be used to help with the purchase of e-bikes.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-18T09:56:04.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901247/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901247/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Electric Vehicles: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to facilitate improved access to and greater uptake of electric bikes in the UK.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","142879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901248","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-18","<p>The Government agrees that electrically assisted pedal cycles (or “e-bikes”), like other forms of cycling, have the potential to deliver significant benefits in relation to air quality and congestion, as well as in many other areas.</p><p> </p><p>We have not carried out any detailed assessment of the potential impact of e-bikes on air quality or congestion, but the Government has regularly encouraged local authorities to consider supporting cycling and walking as ways to improve air quality in their areas.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-18T09:59:26.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901248/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901248/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Electric Vehicles: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of an increase in the uptake of electric bikes on air quality and congestion.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","142880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901249","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>Local authorities are best placed to determine local waste collection and recycling services in line with legislation and taking into account the services local residents demand. Separate collection of compostable waste is the best way to ensure this material is sent to the most appropriate treatment option and for diverting this waste from landfill, reducing the potential for greenhouse gas emissions.</p><p> </p><p>97% of local authorities in England offer a garden waste collection service, and 50% of local authorities in England offer a dedicated food waste collection service either separately or mixed with garden waste. This waste is typically composted or, in the case of separately collected food waste, sent to anaerobic digestion.</p><p> </p><p>We want to encourage local authorities to follow best practice in the provision of waste collection and recycling services, and have worked with the Waste and Resources Action Programme to provide guidance on separate collection of food waste and on garden waste collection and have committed to working towards no foodwaste entering landfill by 2030.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:22:57.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901249/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901249/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2018 to Question 123768 on Waste Disposal, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to make the separate collection of compostable waste by local authorities mandatory.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","142753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901250","Home Office","false","2018-07-02","<p>The table below sets out the substances identified as being used in attacks between November 2016 and April 2017 based on the returns from 39 police forces as part of the National Police Chiefs’ Council commissioned voluntary data collection. These figures must be treated with caution, as they are not official statistics. Furthermore, they are only available for cases where the substance was recorded by officers and reflect what the officers involved in the case believed the substance to be, based on the available evidence.</p><p>Indicative figures for 408 acid or corrosive attacks broken down by substance <br>Acid 56<br>Ammonia 69<br>Bleach 71<br>Other stated substance 107<br>Unknown liquid 74<br>No information provided 31<br>Total 408<br> <br>Other stated substance included a range of diverse substances including boiling water, lighter fluid, petrol, CS and pepper spray and non-ammonia/bleach household cleaning products.</p><p><br>The National Police Chiefs’ Council lead has undertaken a further data collection exercise with police forces to provide us with updated figures on the extent of corrosive substance attacks. We expect that the exercise will be completed shortly and will help inform our assessment on the current incidence and risk of corrosive substances being used in violent attacks.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-07-02T13:40:16.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901250/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901250/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the (a) level of incidence and (b) risk of the use in violent crime of (i) phosphoric acid, (ii) hydrochloric acid, (iii) sodium hydroxide, (iv) ammonia and (v) hydrofluoric acid.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","142821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901251","Home Office","false","2018-05-17","<p>The “Sell Chemical Products Responsibly” leaflet was re-issued following amendments to Schedule 1A to the Poisons Act 1972 laid on 3 April. It was designed with face to face transactions in mind, providing some indicators of suspicious transactions as well as how to identify products of concern and report suspicions. Specific, tailored guidance has been shared with online retailers to support their reporting obligation under the same Act.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-05-17T14:08:14.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901251/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901251/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Chemicals: Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the updated leaflet entitled Sell Chemical Products Responsibly, published by her Department on 4 April 2018, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of that leaflet in giving guidance to online retailers on their statutory duty to report suspicious purchases under the Poisons Act 1972.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","142822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901252","Home Office","false","2018-06-14","<p>The information requested is not available in Home Office published statistics. DNA tests are not required and if the applicant chooses to submit one it will be considered along with the other evidence submitted to support a visa application.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-14T17:02:03.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901252/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901252/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Visas: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department,  how many visa applicants seeking to join a family member in the UK had a DNA test to evidence their relationship to that family member in each year for which information is available; and how many of those DNA tests proved that the relationship between the visa applicant and their family member living in the UK was as they claimed it to be.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","142891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901253","Home Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Home Office is working with Thames Valley Police to support the policing operation around the wedding of Prince Harry and Ms Markle. The Thames Valley Police and Crime Commissioner has not applied for Special Grant funding at this point, but any such application will be considered carefully.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-05-15T12:04:01.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901253/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901253/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Prince Harry: Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2018 to question 135723, on Prince Harry: Marriage,  whether Thames Valley Police have submitted an application to her Department for Special Grant funding for additional costs associated with policing the royal wedding.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","142892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901255","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-17","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) remains committed to enforcing international maritime regulations.</p><p> </p><p>Rationalising the Marine Office network sits alongside the introduction of remote working so that Marine Surveyors can be located closer to where the MCA’s services are most required. This work is not yet complete. Once completed, the effectiveness of the changes will be reviewed.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-05-17T12:16:56.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901255/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901255/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Maritime and Coastguard Agency
","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of changes to the Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA) national network of marine offices on the MCA’s capacity to enforce international maritime regulations.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","142836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901256","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Government is committed to increasing participation in level 3 mathematics to ensure the future workforce is skilled, competitive and productive. Since 2004, entries to A level mathematics have risen by 83% (84,226 in 2017). It is now the most popular A level and taken by 23.8% of students taking academic qualifications. There are currently over 250 students attending the two open mathematics schools sponsored by King’s College London and Exeter University along with Exeter College.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has already implemented a number of the recommendations made by the Smith Review. A funding incentive has been introduced to help schools and colleges increase participation in post-16 academic mathematics qualifications. The advanced maths premium will provide up to £600 per additional student studying academic level 3 mathematics qualifications.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has reduced the requirements for an additional payment that supports those 16 to 19 year olds who are undertaking a greater number of subjects post 16. The changes aim to provide a further financial incentive for promoting the further mathematics A level. Students will now need to achieve a grade C rather than a grade B in their further mathematics A level for their school or college to receive this additional payment</p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to fund centrally delivered professional development programmes for core maths, AS/A levels mathematics and further mathematics. A new Advanced Mathematics Support Programme (AMSP), worth £16 million over two years, started on the 1 May.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also working with the Royal Society’s Advisory Committee on Maths Education to embed occupation-specific maths within the technical qualification component of each of the new T levels.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-15T15:41:48.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901256/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901256/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","16-18 Mathematics Education Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress has been made on implementing the recommendations of the Smith Review of post-16 mathematics since its publication on 20 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","142743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901257","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-15","<p>Ministers from across Government have carried out extensive engagement on EU exit - with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy and in all parts of the UK, including representatives from UK ports.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Lord Bridges, then Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Department for Exiting the European Union, made an official visit to the Port of Tilbury, in October 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Details of ministerial meetings are published in the Department's Quarterly Transparency Returns, which are made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-05-15T15:04:37.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901257/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901257/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-10","Ports: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he or Ministers of his Department have made an official visit to the Port of London since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","142865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901258","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-15","<p>Ministers from across Government have carried out extensive engagement on EU exit - with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy and in all parts of the UK, including representatives from UK ports.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Details of DExEU Ministerial visits to UK ports since July 2016 are as follows:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>October 2016, Lord Bridges, Port of Tilbury</p></li><li><p>November 2016, Lord Bridges, Port of Felixstowe</p></li><li><p>December 2016, David Jones, Port of Southampton</p></li><li><p>December 2016, David Jones, Port of Liverpool</p></li><li><p>July 2017, Robin Walker, Poole Harbour</p></li><li><p>September 2017, Robin Walker, Belfast Harbour</p></li><li><p>January 2018, David Davis and Suella Braverman, Teesport</p></li><li><p>March 2018, Suella Braverman, Port of Southampton</p></li><li><p>May 2018, Suella Braverman, Port of Dover</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings are published in the Department's Quarterly Transparency Returns, which are made publicly available on GOV.UK. The next set of Transparency Returns will be released in June.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-05-15T15:11:02.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901258/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901258/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-10","Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which of the UK’s ports (a) he and (b) other Ministers in of his Department have visited since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","142866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901259","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-15","<p>Ministers and officials have regular meetings and discussions with social media companies on a range of issues including the removal of hate speech and extreme content. Details of ministerial meetings are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-05-15T09:39:52.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901259/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901259/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-10","Social Media: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent meetings he has had with leading social media companies to discuss the prevalence, removal and prevention of hate speech and other extreme content on social media platforms.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","142759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901260","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-18","<p>The UK does not have access to sufficient information to allow us to make accurate assessments of the effects of every individual action taken by the Saudi-led Coalition.</p><p>We are acutely aware that during armed conflict civilians often pay a heavy price. This underlines the imperative of reaching a political solution to the crisis. Peace talks are the top priority, as there can be no military solution to the conflict. A political settlement is the only way to bring long-term stability to Yemen and to address the worsening humanitarian crisis. The Yemeni parties must engage constructively and in good faith to overcome obstacles and find a political solution to end the conflict.​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-18T11:30:00.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901260/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901260/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of effect on the local population of the recent Saudi-led coalition airstrikes on the business district in Sana'a, Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","142760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901261","Home Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Government is in full support of the Military Covenant and its application across the UK.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-15T13:15:49.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901261/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901261/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","UK Border Force: Armed Forces Covenant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the answer of 8 May 2018 to Question 140136 on UK Border Force: Northern Ireland, whether the UK Border Agency (a) supports the Military Covenant and (b) recognises its UK-wide applicability.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","142875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901262","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government has no plans to commission an assessment on the need for more animal rendering plants.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has around 40 rendering plants which perform an important role in protecting public and animal health. Decisions on the need for additional plants are guided by market demand and local planning policy.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-21T09:19:24.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901262/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901262/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Livestock: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has commissioned an independent assessment on the need for more animal rendering plants; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Caroline Johnson","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Dr Caroline Johnson","142911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901263","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-16","<p>The Department’s consultation on how Regulation 1071/2009 applies to permits under the Transport Act 1985 has now closed and over 500 responses have been received. The Department will analyse the responses fully and provide a summary response before summer recess. The consultation included a potential exemption relating to operators that may have minimal impact owing to the short distances involved.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-16T15:52:06.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901263/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901263/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Motor Vehicles: Licensing and Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to exempt small not-for-profit community groups from proposed additional licensing and vehicle testing conditions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne","142740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901264","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-18","<p>The attached page from the July 2012 version of the Tornado Aircrew Manual provides details of the minimum ejection heights. This version remains current.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-05-18T12:51:48.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901264/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901264/answer","20180515-AircrewManual.pdf","20180515-AircrewManual.pdf","Minimum Ejection Heights","Minimum Ejection Heights","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901264/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-10","Tornado Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 30 April 2018 to question 136899, if he will provide details of the minimum safe height/sink rate/speed/bank angle envelope, as stated in the tornado aircrew manual.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","142876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901265","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-17","<p>We are investing in the biggest upgrade of the Midland Main Line since it was completed in 1870. This infrastructure upgrade will create capacity for up to 50% more seats in the peak into London St Pancras.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with Network Rail on the upgrade, and based on their plans and projections at this time, delivery is expected in 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We will shortly be announcing the Invitation to Tender for the next East Midlands franchise, which will set out how we want to see the next operator make best use of this additional capacity. For journeys between Corby and London, the consultation on the next East Midlands franchise proposed that passengers benefit from a new and dedicated express service. From 2020, it was proposed that the trains would be fast, like today, but also longer, with more seats.</p><p> </p><p>This would enable the next operator of the East Midlands franchise to resume peak-time services at Bedford and Luton.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-17T12:13:34.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901265/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901265/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","East Midlands Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether improvements to infrastructure and the capacity for East Midlands Trains will be completed in 2020; and what steps his Department is taking to prevent delays to services serving stations along that route post-2020.","false","Biography information for Bim Afolami","Hitchin and Harpenden","Bim Afolami","142918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901266","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Government’s priority is to maintain an effective regulatory system for managing and controlling chemicals to safeguard human health and the environment, responding to emerging risks and allowing trade with the EU that is as smooth as possible. The Withdrawal Bill will convert current EU law into domestic law wherever practical, giving consumers and businesses as much certainty as possible. This includes laws relating to chemicals. REACH will continue to apply while the UK remains in the EU, and during the implementation period.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister set out in her Mansion House speech, we will want to explore with the EU the terms on which we could remain part of EU agencies, such as the European Chemicals Agency (ECHA). While it would not be appropriate to pre-judge the outcome of the negotiations we are discussing with the EU and Member States how best to continue cooperation in chemicals regulation in the best interests of both the UK and the EU.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-22T14:51:50.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901266/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901266/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Chemicals: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to ensure that the framework for the regulation of chemicals provided by the EU Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation & Restriction of Chemicals regulation will be replicated in the UK after it leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","142900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901267","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-16","<p>DFID Zimbabwe Programme Spend for the past five years:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Actual Spend (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>105,994,824.16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>68,620,415.12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>85,786,771.83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>104,885,392.21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/2018</p></td><td><p>93,761,324.33</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>459,048,727.66</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-16T14:57:18.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901267/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901267/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Zimbabwe: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much financial assistance her Department has given to projects in Zimbabwe in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","142772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901268","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-16","<p>DFID has committed £237.5 million in humanitarian support to Iraq since 2014, including £20 million this financial year. This helps provide a vital lifeline to internally displaced people through the provision of emergency food, shelter, medical care and clean water. Additionally, the UK has committed over £30 million to improve conditions in liberated areas in Iraq, for instance by delivering basic services like water and electricity, removing mines and promoting community reconciliation. This will make it easier for internally displaced people from across the region to return safely to their areas of origin.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-16T15:02:38.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901268/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901268/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Iraq: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support internally displaced people in Iraq.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","142773"
