"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901375","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Research Councils monitor and publish annually the diversity data of their applicants which has been extended to include data for successfully appointed students since 2015-16. The data is used to track progress and inform policy. With the creation of UKRI, we recognise there is a real opportunity to build on this data collection and we aim to extend this to include a similar dataset for Innovate UK. UKRI has recently launched the recruitment for establishing an external advisory group and will be developing an equality, diversity and inclusion action plan.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Concordat to Support the Career Development of Researchers 2008 provides a single, unambiguous statement of the expectations and responsibilities of research funders and institutions with respect to the management of researchers/contract research staff. In accordance with this, diversity and equality must be promoted in all aspects of the recruitment and career management of researchers. Vitae leads on its management and implementation, reporting to the Concordat Strategy Group which includes representatives of all the main UK funders and employers of researchers. The Concordat Strategy Group is currently carrying out a ten-year review of the Concordat. The review will be carried out by an independent expert review panel, with a secretariat provided by UKRI and Innovation. A report will be published in September 2018.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-15T12:20:27.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901375/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901375/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the short term project funding model on the diversity of early years researchers.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901376","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-15","<p>Researchers have statutory employment rights as do any other UK employee, irrespective of their career stage. Any other contractual entitlements they may have would vary from employer to employer. PhD students are not necessarily employed by the institution where they are studying.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-15T12:19:29.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901376/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901376/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what employment rights are associated with (a) post-doctoral and (b) project research funding for researchers in the early stage of their careers.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901377","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-15","<p>There is no requirement on local authorities to measure small business access to local authority procurement. As independent contracting authorities, local authorities are responsible for taking their own procurement decisions. While authorities are subject to the requirements of legislation and should have regard to a combination of economy, efficiency and effectiveness, I would strongly encourage councils to consider how the can use their procurement activity to support the local economy and small businesses.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-05-15T16:16:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901377/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901377/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-10","Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what requirements there are for local authorities to measure small business access to local authority procurement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901378","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-15","<p>Certification of the products and the installation by the Microgeneration Certification Scheme (MCS) is a key eligibility requirement for two government incentives, the Renewable Heat Incentive and the Feed-in Tariff. The Department works closely with MCS and Consumer Codes operating in this sector to ensure that consumers using an MCS certified contractor for a renewable energy installation are protected.</p><p> </p><p>Where an installer fraudulently claims to be MCS certified, the consumer can contact their local trading standards office <a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-local-trading-standards-office" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-local-trading-standards-office</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Where the Department receives individual correspondence regarding such cases, officials work closely with Ofgem and MCS to ensure best possible outcomes can be achieved for the consumer.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-05-15T12:23:49.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901378/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901378/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support his Department provides to people who have had renewable energy systems fitted by businesses fraudulently claiming to be MCS accredited and are therefore unable to receive the grants from Ofgem.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","142905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901379","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that current environmental protections will not be weakened after the UK leaves the EU. We are committed to working closely with the devolved administrations to deliver an approach that works for the whole of the UK, whilst also respecting the devolution settlements and the specific needs of each administration.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers and officials are in regular discussion with counterparts in the devolved administrations on environmental policy matters. This includes considering the need for common frameworks after the UK leaves the EU, and how standards set in relevant devolved legislation, such as the Well-being of Future Generations (Wales) Act 2015, should be taken into account in any future framework arrangements agreed between the UK Government and the devolved administrations.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-16T16:12:27.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901379/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901379/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Environment Protection: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will commit to not falling below the standards set in the Well-being of Future Generations (Wales) Act 2015 when establishing common UK frameworks for the environment after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","142779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901380","Treasury","false","2018-05-15","<p>By 2019-20 we will be spending a record £6 billion on childcare support. The IT and call centre costs referred to in my answer to question 137634 are not included within this figure.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-15T13:47:45.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901380/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901380/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the answer of 27 April 2018 to Question 137634, on Children: Day Care, whether support costs will be included as part of the £6bn spend on childcare in 2020.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","142906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901381","Treasury","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Childcare Service is an integrated digital service through which parents can apply for Tax-Free Childcare and 30 hours free childcare in a single application. As the costs of one application can be associated with both policies, there is not a clear distinction between the operating costs of each. In 2017-18, HMRC met just under £29 million of the total costs, and DfE £8 million.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-15T16:14:02.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901381/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901381/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the answer of 27 April 2018 to Question 137634, on 137634, what was the total amount his Department planned to spend on support costs for policies related to childcare and early education in the financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","142907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901382","Department for Education","false","2018-05-15","<p>The government will be investing £1 billion a year to increase our hourly funding rates for the free entitlements and deliver 30 hours of free childcare. These funding rates are based on our ‘Review of Childcare Costs’, which was described as “thorough and wide ranging” by the National Audit Office. This looked at both the current costs of childcare provision and the implications of future cost pressures facing the sector, including the National Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor delivery costs of our early years entitlements and have commissioned new research to provide us with robust and detailed cost data from a representative sample of early years providers.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-15T16:12:50.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901382/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901382/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Pre-school Education: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of the national living wage on the financial viability of early years providers.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","142908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901383","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>The specific data requested is not available. Information on the employer of those individuals sponsoring visa applicants is not collected by the Home Office as it is not required as part of visa application processes.</p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p><p>Should a customer wish to seek compensation they are advised to contact UKVI and they will be dealt with on a case by case basis in accordance with the complaints procedure:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","142915 ; 142916","2018-05-14T16:57:34.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901383/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901383/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Visas: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many employees of universities have applied for visas for their (a) spouses and (b) families in each of the last five years; and how many of those applications have (a) been accepted, b) been rejected and (c) are still pending.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","142914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901384","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>The specific data requested is not available. Information on the employer of those individuals sponsoring visa applicants is not collected by the Home Office as it is not required as part of visa application processes.</p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p><p>Should a customer wish to seek compensation they are advised to contact UKVI and they will be dealt with on a case by case basis in accordance with the complaints procedure:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","142914 ; 142916","2018-05-14T16:57:34.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901384/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time is for his Department to process spousal visas.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","142915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901385","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>The specific data requested is not available. Information on the employer of those individuals sponsoring visa applicants is not collected by the Home Office as it is not required as part of visa application processes.</p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p><p>Should a customer wish to seek compensation they are advised to contact UKVI and they will be dealt with on a case by case basis in accordance with the complaints procedure:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","142914 ; 142915","2018-05-14T16:57:34.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901385/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901385/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what compensation his Department provides to people who experience delays with their spousal visa applications.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","142916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901386","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Home Office publishes a list of Border, Immigration and Citizenship (BIC) application fees and estimated unit costs which can be reviewed via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/691200/Fees_Unit_Cost_Table_-_April_2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/691200/Fees_Unit_Cost_Table_-_April_2018.pdf</a></p><p>(a) A spouse can submit a dependant application under a number of different routes depending on the visa category of their spouse/partner. However, if the individual is making an application to join their spouse/partner who is them self settled in the UK, or a British citizen, they would apply via the Route to Settlement category, which is shown on page 4 of the linked table.</p><p>(b) The estimated unit costs for both In-UK and overseas student visa applications are shown on page 3 of the linked table.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-14T16:55:29.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901386/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901386/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost to UK Visa and Immigration is to process (a) spousal visas and (b) student visas.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","142917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901387","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Government is considering carefully the important issues raised in the Second Report of the Health and Social Care Committee, Nursing Workforce HC353 and plans to publish its response in the coming weeks.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-05-15T12:55:05.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901387/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901387/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-10","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, which his Department plans to respond to the Second Report of the Health and Social Care Committee,  Nursing Workforce, HC353, published on 29 January 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","142927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901388","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-15","<p>It is for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to decide on how local mental health provision should be made, based on local need and circumstances. CCGs are required to work with other local services to produce local transformation plans (LTPs), now included in sustainability and transformation plans, which set out how children and young people’s mental health services will be delivered locally, including in early years.</p><p> </p><p>We are making available an additional £1.4 billion to support them in this. NHS England’s report, ‘Children and young people’s mental health Local Transformation Plans – a summary of key themes’, estimated that almost 90% of LTPs referenced having early years programmes in place. The report is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/mentalhealth/wp-content/uploads/sites/29/2016/08/cyp-mh-ltp.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/mentalhealth/wp-content/uploads/sites/29/2016/08/cyp-mh-ltp.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-05-15T16:23:54.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901388/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901388/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-10","Pre-school Education: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he his taking to increase the number of mental health specialists working in early years settings.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","142909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901389","Treasury","false","2018-05-15","<p>In November 2016 the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) established a complaints process for small and medium-sized enterprises in their Global Restructuring Group (GRG) between 2008-2013, overseen by an independent third party, and took the decision to automatically refund complex fees paid by relevant customers to GRG during that period. RBS have set aside £400m for this scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Following a meeting with the Chief Executive of RBS I received a letter on 9 May stating that RBS have also committed to setting up an independent appeal process for consequential loss claims under the redress scheme.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-15T13:44:25.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901389/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901389/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Royal Bank of Scotland: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the oral contribution of the Economic Secretary to the Treasury of 10 March 2018, Official Report, column 978, what compensation he proposes be provided to the small business customers of Royal Bank of Scotland who were subject to inappropriate behaviour by that company.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","142837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901390","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-17","<p>In addition to the announcement in the autumn budget of an extra £1.6 billion of funding for the National Health Service, the Department added a further £540 million to bring the total to £2.14 billion which was allocated to the NHS as follows:</p><p>- £650 million is added to the Provider Sustainability Fund (previously the Sustainability and Transformation Fund) and so will be paid directly to NHS providers; and</p><p>- £1.49 billion has been allocated to NHS commissioners, predominantly for the purchase of secondary care activity and mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioners are required to detail the total amount of planned expenditure for a given year but are not required to separately account for how the increase in the allocation from the previous year has been allocated, so it is not possible to identify how much of the additional money has been allocated to independent sector providers.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-05-17T10:41:30.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901390/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901390/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-10","Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 2 May 2016 to Question 139056 on Health Services: Finance, how much and what proportion of the £1.6 billion announced in Autumn Budget 2017 for allocation in 2018-19 has been used to commission services by (a) NHS Trusts and (b) independent healthcare providers.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","142928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901391","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-17","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to my answer of 1 December 2017, UIN 116038.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-17T15:43:58.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901391/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901391/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-10","Community Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to support community transport operators.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","142820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901392","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-15","<p>We are considering options for small-scale low-carbon generation beyond 2019, and a consultation on the Feed-in Tariffs scheme will be published in due course.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-05-15T12:23:17.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901392/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901392/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish the consultation on proposals for replacement of the feed-in tariff policy framework.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","142884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901393","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-18","<p>The number of cases reported to the Charity Commission by UK aid charities has increased sharply since the Secretary of State wrote to all of DFID’s major partners in February asking them to confirm that they have referred any and all concerns they have on specific cases to the relevant authorities. As more attention is paid to this topic, we expect reporting to continue to increase as confidence grows that action will be taken. What is clear is that sexual exploitation, abuse and harassment still occurs far too often. That is why the Secretary of State is absolutely determined to drive up safeguarding standards in the aid sector to prevent it occurring, to ensure that victims receive the support they need and to hold perpetrators to account.</p><p> </p><p>Since February 2018, the Secretary of State has established a dedicated Safeguarding Unit; written to all of DFID’s major partners seeking assurance about their safeguarding approach; established new working groups with NGOs, donors and experts to identify and test solutions; and announced new safeguarding standards as part of DFID’s due diligence process. She has also taken this message to the international community, leading a collective letter to the UN Secretary General and hosting or speaking at international roundtables with the United Nations, international financial institutions and other donors, including at the recent World Bank Spring Meetings.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is leading the change needed on this issue. We have made good progress since March and will continue to use every opportunity possible in the coming weeks and months to push for much more. The Secretary of State will host an international conference in London on the 18th October at which she will seek concrete commitments and actions from donors and all of the partners we work with.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-18T13:39:21.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901393/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901393/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Charities: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the level of sexual exploitation within the aid sector; and what steps the Government is taking to tackle it.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","142912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901394","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government shares the British public’s high regard for animal welfare and, after we leave the EU, the Government plans to retain the current regulations banning the import of cat and dog fur and products, and seal skins and products from commercial hunts.</p><p>Any further restrictions on importing fur and fur products after we leave the EU should be based on the protection of animal welfare. The Government is considering the case for further steps.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-21T11:48:17.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901394/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901394/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Furs: Import Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of extending existing fur import bans to cover all species affected by the fur trade.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","142913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901404","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-16","<p>Investigations into competition issues are a matter for the Competition and Markets Authority, the UK’s independent competition authority.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-05-16T13:39:02.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901404/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901404/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Newspaper Press: Wholesale Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of calls by the National Federation of Retail Newsagents for a Competition and Markets Authority inquiry into the absolute territorial protection enjoyed by news wholesalers.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL7731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901405","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-22","<p>The review of the sustainability of high-quality journalism is being led by an external chair, Dame Frances Cairncross, with support from an advisory panel of industry experts. It is for the Chair to determine what analysis and research will be carried out to inform her final report.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside the review, DCMS have commissioned a piece of sector analysis, looking at the changing state of the press market and assessing new business models being deployed by news publishers at a national, regional and local level. We will publish this research in due course.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-05-22T15:02:17.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901405/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901405/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-10","Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of their review of press sustainability in the UK, they will conduct research into (1) sales figures for local and national newspapers since 2010, and (2) which local and regional newspapers have ceased publication since 2010; and if so, whether they will publish any such research.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL7732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901406","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>There is no automatic requirement for water companies to provide and operate specific phosphorus removal treatment at sewage treatment works.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement for such treatment depends on the environmental legislation and standards that apply to the receiving water into which a sewage treatment work discharges. Where a receiving water is a designated sensitive area (eutrophic) under the urban waste water treatment regulations, sewage treatment works of a particular size will require the provision of phosphorus removal treatment to meet standards set out in the regulations. Alternatively, where environmental standards in the receiving water are not achieved to meet the Water Framework Directive regulations and conservation requirements, phosphorus removal treatment may be required at a sewage treatment work.</p><p> </p><p>The requirements for treatment and the limits to be achieved are set out in the environmental permit to discharge for each sewage treatment work which is issued and regulated by the Environment Agency in England.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-05-16T14:46:19.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901406/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901406/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Water Treatment: Phosphates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 8 May (HL7364), whether water companies are required to operate phosphate removal plants.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL7733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901407","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2018-05-22","<p>211 peers are eligible to stand in the forthcoming hereditary by-election and 31 are eligible to vote.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2018-05-22T13:42:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901407/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901407/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker how many peers are eligible to (1) stand, and (2) vote, in the forthcoming hereditary by-election.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901408","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2018-05-22","<p>The costs for the forthcoming Crossbench hereditary peers’ by-election are expected to be similar to those for the last Crossbench hereditary peers’ by-election held in 2017. The total cost to the House of Lords for the services provided by Electoral Reform Services (ERS) in respect of the 2017 by-election was £1,140. This includes VAT at 20%. This is in addition to the cost of House of Lords staff time spent organising the by-election which forms part of their normal duties and is not costed separately.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2018-05-22T13:44:04.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901408/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901408/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker how much the forthcoming hereditary by-election will cost the House Administration to run.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901409","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2018-05-22","<p>In order to be eligible to stand in a by-election, a hereditary peer must petition the House of Lords to be included in the Register maintained by the Clerk of the Parliaments under Standing Order 10(5). The petition is referred to the Lord Chancellor who reports to the House on whether the peer has proved his or her claim to the title and established his or her right to be included in the Register. If the Lord Chancellor is satisfied that the peer has established his or her right, then the peer is added to the Register; but if the Lord Chancellor is not satisfied, then the matter is referred to the Committee for Privileges and Conduct which considers the matter and reports to the House.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2018-05-22T13:45:46.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901409/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901409/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker what are the criteria for the candidates to be eligible to stand in hereditary by-elections.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901410","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2018-05-22","<p>One woman is eligible to stand in the forthcoming hereditary by-election.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2018-05-22T13:46:20.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901410/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901410/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker how many women are eligible to stand in the forthcoming hereditary by-election.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901411","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2018-05-22","<p>The House does not collect data on the ethnic background of those listed in the Register of Hereditary Peers.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2018-05-22T13:47:09.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901411/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901411/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker how many people from black and minority ethnic backgrounds are eligible to stand in the forthcoming hereditary by-election.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901412","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The House of Lords Appointments Commission does not have a role in the hereditary by-election process. Under the Standing Orders of the House, this process is conducted in accordance with arrangements made by the Clerk of the Parliaments.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-05-22T15:01:16.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901412/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901412/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-10","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the role of the House of Lords Appointments Commission in relation to the forthcoming hereditary by-election.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL7739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901413","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-23","<p>Since its launch in 1988, the Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI) has successfully led global efforts that have reduced Wild Polio Virus cases by more than 99% from 350,000 cases a year in 125 countries to eight cases so far this year in only three endemic countries.</p><p>The UK has played a leading role in this process and UK support to the GPEI will mean up to 45 million children can be vaccinated against polio each year until 2020.</p><p>The UK Government has advocated strongly, with all relevant players, that the consequences of a reduction in polio funds (as eradication nears) must be understood and that the benefits of the polio eradication system for wider health systems are realised. The World Health Organisation will present a “Global Polio Transition Strategic Action Plan” to the World Health Assembly at the end of May 2018. The UK will scrutinise this carefully and hold WHO to account for its leadership of this area.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-05-23T16:31:25.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901413/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901413/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to (1) ensure progress made by the Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI) is sustained after polio funding is withdrawn in countries transitioning away from GPEI support in 2019, and (2) minimise the detrimental consequences the transition could have on basic health infrastructure in those countries.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayman",,"Baroness Hayman","HL7740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901414","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Ministerial Code was revised in January 2018 to include new wording to make clear that harassing, bullying or other inappropriate or discriminatory behaviour wherever it takes place is not consistent with the Ministerial Code and will not be tolerated. We will be looking to make similar amendments to the Civil Service Code and the Code of Conduct for Special Advisers in due course.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-05-22T15:02:58.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901414/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901414/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-10","Politics and Government: Sexual Harassment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration they have given to updating (1) the Ministerial Code of Conduct, (2) the Special Advisers Code of Conduct, and (3) the Civil Service Code of Conduct, in response to allegations of sexual harassment and abuse in public life and the awareness raised by the MeToo campaign.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL7741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901415","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>UK law does not currently require such disclosure. However, as my Rt. Hon Friend the Prime Minister announced in the House of Commons on 14 March (Hansard col. 856), as part of an update on the Salisbury incident, the Government is reviewing whether there is a need for new counter-espionage powers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-05-24T15:01:48.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901415/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901415/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what provision there is in UK law for all agents representing the interests of foreign powers in a political or quasi-political capacity to disclose their relationship with a foreign government and information about their activities and finances.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL7742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901416","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-22","<p>UK Export Finance (UKEF) publishes details of its support on an annual basis in its Annual Report and Accounts which are presented to Parliament and can be found on its website, which can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-export-finance-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-export-finance-annual-reports-and-accounts</a></p><p> </p><p>In 2016-17, 79% of UK companies supported by UKEF were small and medium-sized enterprises.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-05-22T16:58:14.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901416/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901416/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-10","Small Businesses: Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what has been the take up to date of finance available to small and medium enterprises and companies through UK Export Finance.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901417","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>​The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><em><strong>Letter from John Pullinger CB, National Statistician, to The Lord Kennedy of Southwark, dated 17 May 2018.</strong></em></p><p> </p><p><em></em></p><p>Dear Lord Kennedy,</p><p> </p><p>As National Statistician and Chief Executive of the UK Statistics Authority, I am responding to your Parliamentary Question asking what the breakdown is, by sector, in the latest overseas trade export figures to the end of March 2018 <strong>(HL7744).</strong></p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics (ONS) trade statistics are currently produced on a product basis and not by industry sector. However, we are engaged in a wide development of UK trade statistics and are working towards producing our trade statistics by industry sector for the latter end of 2018. Further details can be found in our published trade development plan.<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup></p><p> </p><p>You can find data on trade in goods and services in the <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/datasets/3tradeinservicesthepinkbook2016" target="_blank"><em>Quarterly Balance of Payments</em> release. </a>This data is broken down by service type and by goods commodity group. The latest data available is from 2017, and 2018 Quarter 1 data will be released on 29 June 2018. You can find the data on the ONS website[2], Table E for goods and Table F for services.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we produce trade in goods further detail on a quarterly basis by <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/datasets/publicationtablesuktradecpa08" target="_blank"><em>Classification of Product by Activity</em></a>, the latest data for which covers 2017 Quarter 4. This data can be accessed on the ONS website[3]; in Table 1 for total exports, Table 3 for EU exports and Table 5 for non-EU exports:</p><p> </p><p>You may also wish to note the latest export figures at an aggregate level via the UK Trade statistical bulletin[4] and corresponding publication[5].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Yours sincerely,</p><p><strong>John Pullinger </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1]https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/articles/uktradedevelopmentplan/2017</p><p>[2]https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/datasets/balanceofpaymentsstatisticalbulletintables</p><p>[3]https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/datasets/publicationtablesuktradecpa08</p><p>[4]https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/bulletins/uktrade/march2018</p><p>[5]https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/bulletins/uktrade/march2018/relateddata.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-05-22T15:13:13.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901417/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901417/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-10","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the breakdown by sector in the latest overseas trade export figures to the end of March 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901418","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>On 27 March we invited all of the principal Northamptonshire local authorities to make proposals for a restructuring of local government across Northamptonshire. We understand all eight councils, including the county council, are working well together to develop a locally led proposal, and we are confident that the appointment of Commissioners at the County Council will not change this.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-05-22T15:18:02.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901418/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901418/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-10","Local Government: Northamptonshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the appointment of Commissioners to Northamptonshire County Council, what assessment they have made of the implications for any reorganisation of local government in Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901419","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p>Illegal dumping of waste is a serious crime which damages the environment and causes misery to local communities. The government is committed to bearing down on the perpetrators and tackling all forms of waste crime is a government priority. We ensure that the Environment Agency (EA) and local authorities (LAs) have the necessary powers to tackle crime effectively across the waste sector. We brought in regulations earlier in the year to give the EA two additional powers to tackle problem waste sites. This enables the EA to restrict access to a waste site by locking the gates or barring access, and requiring all the waste to be removed from a site, not just the illegally deposited waste.</p><p> </p><p>We have also recently given LAs the power to issue £400 fixed penalty notices for fly-tipping offences and have enhanced the powers available to LAs and the EA, such as the ability to search and seize the vehicles of suspected waste criminals.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year we published our consultation on proposals to introduce a new fixed penalty for householders who pass their waste to a fly-tipper. We also intend to provide updated guidance for householders about how to ensure their waste is disposed of correctly. We are currently analysing consultation responses. Subject to the outcome of the consultation, we will seek to implement the changes later this year. As two thirds of fly-tipping is household waste, these additional measures will help tackle fly-tipping.</p><p> </p><p>We have also committed £30million in additional funding to the EA for waste crime enforcement until March 2022. This means that since 2014, an additional £60million in funding has been committed to the EA.</p><p> </p><p>With effect from April this year HMRC have introduced two changes to the Landfill Tax regime. These changes will further help tackle illegal dumping by making the disposal of waste less profitable.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-05-22T10:55:31.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901419/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901419/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Fly-tipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to combat the illegal dumping of waste.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901420","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-16","<p>In April 2017, the Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings (ASHE) produced by the Office for National Statistics estimates there were 342,000 jobs with pay less than the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and National Living Wage (NLW) held by employees aged 16 and over, this constitutes 1.2% of all UK employee jobs. This represents a slight decrease from 365,000 jobs (1.3%) in 2016. Further information is published on the ONS website (copy attached), including important caveats in interpreting the data.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with the minimum wage. We are clear that anyone entitled to be paid the minimum wage should receive it. We have more than doubled the enforcement budget for the NMW and NLW to £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13 million in 2015/16. In 2017/18, HMRC identified a record number of £15.6 million in arrears for over 200,000 workers.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-05-16T15:58:31.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901420/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901420/answer","The number of UK jobs from 1998 to 2017 paid below the minimum wage by age group, sex, full-time, part-time, region, occupation and industry.xls","The number of UK jobs from 1998 to 2017 paid below the minimum wage by age group, sex, full-time, part-time, region, occupation and industry.xls","ONS: UK jobs paying below min wage","ONS: UK jobs paying below min wage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901420/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Minimum Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the compliance of employers with their requirements to pay the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901421","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The most common form of tax refund scam involves criminals abusing HMRC’s brand by trying to make it look like an email or text has come from HMRC. HMRC has dedicated Customer Protection teams within their Cyber Security Command Centres to combat Phishing (email) and SMiShing (texting) attacks, including those offering spurious tax refunds. They use a range of proactive and reactive techniques to identify and challenge online scams in order to reduce harm to the public.</p><p> </p><p>In the last year, the teams above have identified over 14,000 malicious HMRC-related websites and requested their removal. HMRC also challenge the ownership of misleading sites through formal internet dispute resolution governance. That work has resulted in over 2 million visits to potentially misleading sites being redirected to gov.uk education pages.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC works closely with other government departments and with industry to continue to develop controls to combat tax refund scams.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-05-23T11:38:42.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901421/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901421/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Taxation: Rebates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to combat tax refund scams.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901422","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Armed Forces Pension Schemes are non-contributory, defined benefit, final salary or career average schemes. They remain the only public-sector schemes that do not require their members to contribute to their future pension, and reflect the unique sacrifice the Armed Forces and their families make to this country. The Government has no plans to alter the schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Annual and lifetime allowance limits have reduced. Consequently, more senior officers are breaching their annual and lifetime allowances and incurring a tax charge. Options are available to these individuals to mitigate a tax charge, including using unclaimed tax allowance from previous years or asking their pension scheme to pay the charge out of future benefits. The Department is keeping the impact on retention of the changes under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL7750 ; HL7751","2018-05-21T15:44:11.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901422/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901422/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-10","Armed Forces: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the financial consequences for senior medical consultants in the Armed Forces of the combined effect of annual non-voluntary contributions which the military requires to be made to the Armed Forces Pension Scheme and current limits on annual and lifetime allowances for tax-free pension contributions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL7749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901423","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Armed Forces Pension Schemes are non-contributory, defined benefit, final salary or career average schemes. They remain the only public-sector schemes that do not require their members to contribute to their future pension, and reflect the unique sacrifice the Armed Forces and their families make to this country. The Government has no plans to alter the schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Annual and lifetime allowance limits have reduced. Consequently, more senior officers are breaching their annual and lifetime allowances and incurring a tax charge. Options are available to these individuals to mitigate a tax charge, including using unclaimed tax allowance from previous years or asking their pension scheme to pay the charge out of future benefits. The Department is keeping the impact on retention of the changes under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL7749 ; HL7751","2018-05-21T15:44:11.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901423/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901423/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-10","Armed Forces: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the retention of senior medical consultants in the Armed Forces of the effects of the non-voluntary contributions which the military requires to be made to the Armed Forces Pension Scheme and current limits on annual and lifetime allowances for tax-free pension contributions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL7750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901424","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Armed Forces Pension Schemes are non-contributory, defined benefit, final salary or career average schemes. They remain the only public-sector schemes that do not require their members to contribute to their future pension, and reflect the unique sacrifice the Armed Forces and their families make to this country. The Government has no plans to alter the schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Annual and lifetime allowance limits have reduced. Consequently, more senior officers are breaching their annual and lifetime allowances and incurring a tax charge. Options are available to these individuals to mitigate a tax charge, including using unclaimed tax allowance from previous years or asking their pension scheme to pay the charge out of future benefits. The Department is keeping the impact on retention of the changes under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL7749 ; HL7750","2018-05-21T15:44:12.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901424/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901424/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-10","Armed Forces: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of compulsory contributions by members of the military to the Armed Forces Pension Scheme in the light of the current limits on annual and lifetime allowances for tax-free pension contributions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL7751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901425","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-16","<p>The British Government is fully committed to involving all the UK Overseas Territories in our planning as we leave the EU, and ensuring that their interests are properly taken into account.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>UK Ministers and leaders of the Overseas Territories discuss EU Exit in the UK Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council on EU Exit Negotiations, which will meet for the fourth time on 14 June this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The British Government has also considered and responded to the evidence presented by Overseas Territories' representatives to the European Union Select Committee on the impact of EU Exit in July of last year.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-05-16T10:58:42.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901425/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901425/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-10","British Overseas Territories: Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with each of the UK Overseas Territories about the specific implications of Brexit for individual Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901426","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-23","<p>At both the 2016 and 2017 Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Councils, the Government of the United Kingdom and the leaders of the Overseas Territories agreed that the fundamental structure of their constitutional relationships was the right one. Powers have been devolved to the elected Governments of the territories wherever possible, consistent with the United Kingdom retaining those powers necessary to discharge its sovereign responsibilities. They also agreed the need to ensure that constitutional arrangements developed effectively to promote the best interests of the Territories and of the United Kingdom.​ This is a matter for continuing discussion between the UK and those Territories.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-05-23T14:13:53.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901426/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901426/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","British Overseas Territories: Self-determination of States","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any discussions, including informal discussions, have been held with any of the UK Overseas Territories since 2016 about greater self-determination.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901427","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>We share with many the desire to see an end to this conflict. We remain of the view that the best way to achieve this remains a two-state solution negotiated between the parties, to be pursued with urgency. We regularly press both parties to resume direct negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-05-22T11:43:11.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901427/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901427/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they will take to combat uncertainty in the Middle East in view of the delay in the release of the United States' Israeli–Palestinian peace plan.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901428","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>We were pleased to see and we welcome the fact that Lebanon's elections took place peacefully and in an orderly way on 6 May. This was an important step for democracy. We now look forward to the swift formation of a new government capable of addressing the crucial issues facing the country. The United Kingdom remains steadfast in its commitment to Lebanon's stability, security and prosperity.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-05-24T10:55:11.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901428/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901428/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Lebanon: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the results of the Lebanese parliamentary election which took place on 6 May; and what impact results will have on their foreign policy approach in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901429","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>We have not discussed knife violence in London with the White House following the President's remarks. We are confident that the US Government is aware via its Embassy of the action we are taking action to restrict access to offensive weapons as well as working to break the deadly cycle of violence and protect our children, families and communities.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-05-24T11:06:06.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901429/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901429/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","USA: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have contacted the White House in response to President Trump’s comments on knife violence in London in his speech to the National Rifle Association convention on 4 May.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901430","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-16","<p>The government recognises the threats posed by invasive non-native species. As part of our comprehensive Great Britain Non-native Species Strategy, we carry out horizon-scanning for new invasive non-native species likely to pose a significant risk if they arrive in the UK. We implement stringent biosecurity measures to prevent their arrival and take action to respond to sightings and rapidly eradicate new invaders where feasible.</p><p> </p><p>There are several invasive non-native mosquito species that are spreading in Europe. The Asian tiger mosquito and closely related yellow fever mosquito are two of the key species that, as well as causing significant nuisance to the public, are vectors for serious diseases, such as Chikungunya, Dengue and Zika.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England has run a surveillance system for invasive mosquitoes since 2010. This includes surveillance at more than 30 United Kingdom sea and airports, at the largest used tyre importers, and at motorway service stations in south east England on the main routes from the south coast ferry ports and Eurotunnel. The surveillance combines a number of traps that detect mosquito eggs, host-seeking and blood-fed mosquitoes and larval sampling. Any findings are followed up with local authorities and appropriate control measures instituted.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-05-16T10:57:09.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901430/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901430/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Mosquitoes: Pest Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to prevent the spread of invasive non-native mosquito species, including the Asian Tiger mosquito.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL7757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901431","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The UK and the EU have reached agreement on the terms of an implementation period that will start on 30 March 2019 and last until 31 December 2020. At the end of the implementation period, there will be a customs, VAT and excise system that enables trade to flow, HMRC to collect revenues, and the UK to have a secure border. Future customs arrangements are subject to negotiation with the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-05-23T11:36:56.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901431/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901431/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Customs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the feasibility of implementing each of the customs models set out in the Customs White Paper by the end of the transition period.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901432","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The costs to businesses of implementing the model would depend on the details agreed as part of the negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-05-23T11:37:17.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901432/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901432/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-10","Customs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the cost to business of implementing the New Customs Partnership model.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901433","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-17","<p>The Government continues to prepare plans for all exit scenarios. During an implementation period, common rules would remain in place and market access would continue on current terms, in order to provide certainty for businesses and citizens. The precise nature of our future relationship with the EU after an implementation period is still to be determined and is the subject of negotiation. The UK Government is aiming to achieve the freest possible trade in goods and services between the UK and the EU, consistent with taking back control of our money, borders, laws and trade.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-05-17T13:22:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901433/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901433/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Animal Products: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress has been made in ensuring the UK will be added to the EU's list of approved third countries for imports of products of animal origin; and what action is being taken to ensure continued reciprocal access for movements of those products from the EU, and, in particular, from the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901434","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-23","<p>As the Prime Minister has previously said, the government does not propose to give a running commentary on negotiations, but standards concerning products of animal origin and animal movements are being given detailed consideration by my department.</p><p> </p><p>Leaving the EU does not change our top priority which is to ensure that UK food remains safe and labelling is accurate. Defra is working closely with the Food Standards Agency and Department of Health and Social Care to ensure that the regulatory regime for food safety remains robust as the UK leaves the EU, in order to protect public health and retain the confidence of consumers and international trading partners.</p><p>From day one we are committed to having in place a robust and effective regulatory regime which will mean business can continue as normal. As we develop our new approach to food and farming outside the EU, we will not compromise on our high standards of animal welfare.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-05-23T12:05:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901434/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901434/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-10","Animal Products: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to table their proposals around rules of animal origin so negotiations are structured around a UK proposal rather than the EU's standard text.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901435","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-24","<p>The UK and EU have agreed that the UK is to be treated as a Member State for the purposes of international agreements during the Implementation Period. This is a positive and significant step to secure continuity in our international trading relationships as we leave the EU.</p><p>Discussions on this approach are taking place with our trading partners, and many have already issued public statements in support of the approach.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-05-24T11:11:23.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901435/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901435/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-10","Overseas Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have secured continued recognition from any third countries that the UK will be treated as an EU member state for trading purposes during the transition period.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901436","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-22","<p>The United Kingdom has a long tradition of close scientific collaboration with the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) which we greatly value and hope to continue in the future. A range of options are being considered for the future of risk assessment and scientific advice in the UK. The nature of the UK’s future relationship with EFSA will be subject to forthcoming negotiations. After the UK has left the European Union, our priority will be to maintain the UK’s high standards of food and feed safety.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-05-22T13:06:08.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901436/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901436/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-10","Food: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the UK food and drink industry will maintain access to the risk assessment expertise of the European Food Safety Authority until a UK scientific risk assessment body is fully functioning.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL7763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901437","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Government has reviewed all existing prison service operational polices and started the process of either cancelling these where they are no longer relevant, or replacing them with Policy Frameworks. Policy Frameworks will contain clear minimum mandatory requirements to ensure a safe, decent and lawful prison system, with consistency across the estate where necessary. To date, under the Government’s deregulation programme, 212 operational prison polices have been cancelled.</p><p> </p><p>Policy Frameworks are currently being developed in a number of areas under a rolling programme. We expect to publish several Policy Frameworks during 2018/19, including those which contain the key levers for prison reform and the rehabilitation of offenders. Policy Frameworks will be published on the Government’s website, in line with the practice for existing prison operational policies.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-05-22T17:02:02.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901437/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901437/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-10","Prisons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to publish further details about plans to cancel all prison service instructions and replace them with a national policy framework.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL7764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901438","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-17","<p>The Government supports the implementation, in full or in part, of nine of the ten recommendations made by the Farmer Review. We have already incorporated the review’s findings and recommendations into policy development. This includes measures to increase housing supply in the Housing White Paper, a review of the Construction Industry Training Board (CITB), additional funding for adult retraining in construction skills and a ‘presumption in favour of offsite construction’ (by 2019) across five major procuring Departments. In addition, Mark Farmer is chairing a stakeholder group (for MHCLG) which is examining barriers to finance for offsite housing.</p><p>Importantly, the Industrial Strategy White Paper (November 2017) announced an ambitious Sector Deal for construction to transform construction productivity by boosting innovation, increasing adoption of digital and manufacturing technologies, and improving procurement and the supply of skills to the sector. This is underpinned by £170m investment in R&amp;D in the sector from the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund. Going forward, Government and the Construction Leadership Council will continue to support the modernisation agenda set out in the Farmer Review through implementation of the Sector Deal.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-05-17T15:24:03.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901438/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901438/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-10","Construction Labour Market in the UK Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress they have made in implementing the recommendations of the Farmer Review of the UK construction labour model.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL7765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901439","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>Children from Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities are able to take advantage of early years education provision. Since 2013, over half a million of the country’s most disadvantaged two year olds, including those from Gypsy Roma and Traveller populations, have benefitted from 15 hours of free early education a week, and can continue this early education with 15 hours of free early education at ages 3 and 4. In the recently published strategy ‘Unlocking Talent, Fulfilling Potential’ a copy of which is available in the Library of the House of Lords, an ambition was laid out to close the word gap backed by over £100 million of investment. Once a child is at school the Pupil Premium is provided, an additional funding provision that continues with nearly £2.5 billion this year alone, to help schools improve the progress and attainment of their disadvantaged pupils. High proportions of Gypsy Roma and Traveller pupils are eligible for and benefit from this support.</p><p> </p><p>The department also provides a number of financial support programmes for economically disadvantaged 16 to 19 year olds to help with the costs associated with staying in post 16 education such as travel and course equipment.</p><p> </p><p>The department is taking action to ensure that high quality apprenticeships are accessible to all. The Apprenticeships Diversity Champions Network and recently launched partnership with five major cities in England, aim to drive up apprenticeships among underrepresented groups.</p><p> </p><p>In Higher Education, providers will now be required to publish application data broken down by ethnicity and those charging higher fees will be required to agree Access and Participation Plans. The plans will set out measures to support the access and successful participation for disadvantaged and under-represented groups, including those from Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2018 the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller stakeholder group was established to inform policy development to raise the attainment and participation of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils at all stages of education. In March 2018 a review of exclusions was launched, exploring why certain pupil groups, including Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils, are over-represented in exclusions statistics. The department continues to collaborate with the Ministry for Housing, Communities and Local Government on their 2018-19 pilot programme to improve the social integration of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities. In addition as part of the Careers Strategy, Gypsy, Roma and Traveller youth will be included as a target group for a pilot testing ways of providing guidance on routes into careers to vulnerable groups.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL7696","2018-05-23T11:32:24.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901439/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901439/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Education and Training: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what strategies are in place to improve access for Gypsy, Traveller and Roma young people to (1) further education, (2) higher education, and (3) apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL7766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901440","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-24","<p>The future of the Assurance and Compliance process for Chaplaincy will be discussed with those Faith Advisers who sit on Chaplaincy Council at the joint meeting with the Chaplaincy HQ Team on the 12th June 2018. This will be followed by an invitation for those Faith Advisers not present at the meeting to comment by post or email.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the importance of faith and the positive impact that it can have on the lives of offenders, which is why there are multi-faith chaplaincy teams in every prison.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-05-24T11:08:45.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901440/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901440/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-10","Prisons: Ministers of Religion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Keen of Elie on 4 January (HL4280), what meetings they have had about the development of the assurace and compliance process for the future delivery of chaplaincies in prisons; and which faith leaders have been involved in any such discussions.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL7767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901442","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-24","<p>Whilst the future policy framework(s) in relation to chaplaincy have not yet been agreed, HM Government recognises the value of the pastoral care offered by Chaplains. Any new policy will ensure such care is available in a timely manner which reflects its importance in the overall care of those in prison.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-05-24T11:08:19.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901442/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901442/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-10","Prisons: Ministers of Religion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the current requirement for a prisoner to receive a pastoral visit from a chaplain within 24 hours of requesting one will be carried into any future policy framework.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL7768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901443","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) collects and publishes statistics on students studying at UK higher education institutions (HEIs).</p><p> </p><p>The following table, which is attached, is taken from HESA’s publication ‘UK Performance Indicators 2016/17: Widening participation’. It shows the distribution of entry qualifications for UK domiciled young entrants to full-time first degrees in education subjects and compares this with the distribution across all subjects.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2018-05-22T16:05:42.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901443/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901443/answer","HL 7769 - Table WP2.doc","HL 7769 - Table WP2.doc","Table_WP2","Table_WP2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901443/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Teachers: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the average A-level achievement of those entering Bachelor of Education degree courses.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL7769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901444","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-22","<p>Article 50 is the only lawful way to withdraw from the Union under the EU Treaties. Article 50 should be considered as a whole and sets out all the relevant procedures for a legal withdrawal. The UK is a law-abiding country and does not pick and choose which of its obligations to abide by and which to ignore. Negotiating and concluding a Withdrawal Agreement as provided for under Article 50 is in the interests of both the UK and the EU.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-05-22T15:54:50.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901444/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901444/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-10","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Callanan on 10 May (HL7529), why leaving the EU in accordance with Article 50(1) without being bound by Articles 50(2) and 50(3) would prevent the UK from being a law abiding country under international treaty law and practice.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL7770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901445","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-24","<p>There are 52 local authorities in England due to hold local elections in May 2019 that have been subject to, or are currently the subject of, an electoral review conducted by the Local Government Boundary Commission for England. Those authorities are: Allerdale; Ashford; Babergh; Basingstoke and Deane; Bath and North East Somerset; Bolsover; Carlisle; Cheshire West and Chester; Chichester; Copeland; Crawley; Dartford; Dover; East Cambridgeshire; East Devon; East Hampshire; Eastbourne; Forest of Dean; Harborough; Hertsmere; Horsham; King's Lynn and West Norfolk; Lewes; Mid Suffolk; North Devon; North East; Derbyshire; North Norfolk; Norwich; Nottingham; Preston; Redcar and Cleveland; Reigate and Banstead; Ribble Valley; Richmondshire; Rother; Runnymede; Rutland; Scarborough; South Gloucestershire; South Norfolk; South Somerset; Surrey Heath; Teignbridge; Tendring; Test Valley; Tewkesbury; Torbay; Torridge; Warwick; Wealden; West Berkshire; and Windsor and Maidenhead.</p><p>Full details of all current and previous reviews are published on the Commission’s website <a href="http://www.lgbce.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.lgbce.org.uk/</a></p><p>The Commission intends to lay any outstanding orders for Parliamentary approval by, at the latest, Christmas recess.</p><p>In addition, there is an expectation that the Commission is likely to undertake electoral reviews of the five new district councils – Bournemouth, Christchurch and Poole; Dorset; East Suffolk; Somerset West and Taunton; and West Suffolk – which would be established by the secondary legislation that Parliament has recently approved, and which provides for their first elections to be held in May 2019.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-05-24T15:06:21.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901445/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901445/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-10","Local Government: Constituencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which local authorities in England that are due to hold elections in May 2019 have been subject to boundary reviews conducted by the Local Government Boundary Commission for England; which of those boundary reviews have already received parliamentary approval; and when they expect to lay the remaining orders before Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL7771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901446","Home Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Home Office has plans to reduce the number of outstanding undecided asylum claims. Part of this included the creation of a new team in Bootle which has been established to help tackle older cases in the asylum system. This team has been designed to establish and roll out best practice in the management of older cases.</p><p>Across the business, fully trained asylum decision makers are expected to carry out five interviews or decisions a week. Staff who are not meeting this will be offered support and more training as part a personal improvement plan.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-05-22T11:38:43.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901446/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901446/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the reported working practices in the office of the Next Generation Casework project requiring staff to meet targets or face disciplinary action, in relation to the handling of asylum cases.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7772"
